    <item>
      <title>Shell autocompletion</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/docs/labs/assignments/sections/auto_comp/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/docs/labs/assignments/sections/auto_comp/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;shell-autocompletion&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Shell autocompletion&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#shell-autocompletion&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;For comfort, your shell should allow you to autocomplete commands, in (at least) two ways: Tab-completion and history-based completion.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;tab-completion&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Tab completion&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#tab-completion&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This feature suggests &amp;ldquo;smart&amp;rdquo; completions of the current command, like possible arguments, options, paths, etc.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote class=&#34;book-hint info&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Example.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&#xA;On most operating systems, the command &lt;code&gt;cd&lt;/code&gt; (like &amp;ldquo;Change Directory&amp;rdquo;) allows you to change the current directory.&#xA;E.g.:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;cd workspace&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;allows you to navigate (from the current folder) to the subfolder called &lt;code&gt;workspace&lt;/code&gt; (if it exists).&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
